messages[71]{time,role,kind,text}:
  "00:01:03",assistant,text,"Now rewrite `Normal.exp3.json` to match the boot face — blush on, smile on (matching the idle's held values), eyes/mouth still free so motions read clean:"
  "00:01:09",assistant,text,"Now register `Content` in the three places that make `vape feeling content` resolve — model manifest, capabilities, and the renderer map:"
  "00:01:19",assistant,text,"Let me validate every JSON I touched:"
  "00:02:05",assistant,text,"Done — all valid. Here's the result:\n\n| `uv run vape feeling …` | face |\n|---|---|\n| **`normal`** | smile + blush — now matches the `vape start` boot face (rewrote `Normal.exp3.json`: `PARAM_TERE 0→1`, `PARAM_MOUTH_FORM 0.3→1`) |\n| **`content`** | the old flat, no-blush resting face (new `Content.exp3.json`) |\n\nWiring touched, so `content` actually resolves end-to-end:\n- `shizuku.model3.json` — added the `Content` expression definition\n- `capabilities.json` — added `content` to the feelings map (interface contract)\n- `index.html` — added `content: 'Content'` to `EXPRESSION_MAP`\n\nBoth keep eyes and mouth-open **un-overwritten**, so motions like `laugh` still read clean over either.\n\n**One thing: you need a full `uv run vape stop && uv run vape start` to see it.** Expression files, the model manifest, and the renderer's `EXPRESSION_MAP` all load at model-init / page-load — a running webview won't pick them up live. After the restart:\n- `uv run vape feeling normal` → boot face (blush + smile)\n- `uv run vape feeling content` → flat\n\nNote one behavioral consequence: since `normal` now holds blush + smile via `Overwrite`, any code path that resets to `normal` will land on the blushing face, not the flat one — that's the intent, just flagging it. The flat reset is now `content`.\n\nWant me to (a) run the restart and verify, and/or (b) add `content` + update the `normal` line in your `curated_feeling_and_expression.md` (and the full list in `feeling_and_expression_commands.md`)?"
  "00:02:08",assistant,text,"Changes are in place and validated. Just say the word on the restart-and-verify and the doc updates, and I'll handle them."
  "00:03:54",user,text,"sorry please switch between normal and content, and keep the content to be on boot"
  "00:04:23",assistant,text,"Got it — swap them: **`content` = boot face (smile + blush)**, **`normal` = flat**. Since the two files differ only in `PARAM_MOUTH_FORM` and `PARAM_TERE`, I'll just swap those values."
  "00:04:44",assistant,text,"Swapped and verified:\n\n| `uv run vape feeling …` | face |\n|---|---|\n| **`content`** | smile + blush — **matches the `vape start` boot face** |\n| **`normal`** | flat, no blush |\n\nThe boot face is idle-driven (smile + blush), and `content` now matches it — so `content` is the on-boot look, exactly as you asked. Registration is unchanged (both already wired), so no other files needed touching.\n\nStill needs a `uv run vape stop && uv run vape start` to load (expressions/manifest/`EXPRESSION_MAP` are read at init). After that:\n- `uv run vape feeling content` → boot face (blush + smile)\n- `uv run vape feeling normal` → flat\n\nWant me to run the restart and verify, or update the docs (`content`/`normal` lines)?"
  "00:20:48",user,text,"now fix that several action like giggle\nlaugh did not work when not in content feeling state"
  "00:21:54",assistant,text,"Got it — this is the masking problem we identified: when a feeling expression with `Blend: \"Overwrite\"` is active, it re-stamps the eye/mouth parameters *every frame after the motion runs*, so motions that animate eyes/mouth (laugh, giggle, …) get clobbered. They \"work in content\" only because `content`/`normal` don't overwrite eye/mouth. Let me research the exact conflict surface and the library API before proposing a fix."
  "00:24:26",assistant,text,"The exploration confirms the root cause and scope precisely:\n\n- **Expressions apply *after* motions each frame**, so any feeling with `Blend:\"Overwrite\"` on `PARAM_EYE_*_OPEN` / `PARAM_MOUTH_OPEN_Y` masks the motion. **13 of 15 feelings** do this — only `Normal` and `Content` are \"safe,\" which is exactly why actions work in those states and nowhere else.\n- The motions that visibly break are the eye/mouth ones: **laugh, giggle, surprisedGasp, celebrate** (mouth + eyes) and the eye-only ones (nod, headShake, headTilt, think, sweat, wave, bow).\n- The library exposes two promising levers — `config.preserveExpressionOnMotion` and `MotionState.shouldOverrideExpression()` — but their exact semantics (does the always-on idle motion also suspend the expression?) need verifying before I build on them.\n\nLet me have a Plan agent nail the library semantics and design the implementation."
  "00:27:41",assistant,text,"Excellent — the Plan agent verified the exact mechanism from the minified source. The linchpin is one config flag, plus a small safety-net for looping motions. Two things I want to confirm myself before writing the plan: the **exact `config` export path** (if wrong, the flag silently no-ops) and the **`shouldOverrideExpression` guard**."
  "00:27:59",assistant,text,"Guard and auto-reset/restore confirmed: `!config.preserveExpressionOnMotion && currentPriority>1` — idle(1) is safe, FORCE(3) self-expressions trigger reset-on-start and restore-on-finish; default is `true` (the bug). Now I must confirm the runtime path to that `config` object so the flag isn't a silent no-op."
  "00:29:15",assistant,text,"Critical check before I commit to this: once I flip the flag, the **idle motion's priority** decides everything. The guard is `currentPriority > 1`, so if the always-looping idle runs at `NORMAL(2)` rather than `IDLE(1)`, flipping the flag would suspend **every** feeling permanently. Let me verify the idle priority and `model.motion()`'s default."
  "00:29:37",assistant,text,"`model.motion('Idle', 0)` → `startMotion('Idle', 0, undefined)`. The auto-idle system uses `IDLE(1)` (safe), but the **explicit init call's** default priority is what matters — if it defaults to `NORMAL(2)` and idle loops forever, the fix breaks. Let me find `startMotion`'s priority default."
  "00:29:45",assistant,text,"That's the low-level queue manager's `startMotion`. I need `MotionManager.startMotion(group, index, priority)` — the one `model.motion` calls. Let me find it and its priority default."
  "00:30:27",assistant,text,Found the signal — there's a `NORMAL` default. Let me read the full `startMotion` signature to confirm the priority default and the reserve logic.
  "00:31:52",assistant,text,"Verified the full chain from the minified source. The key findings:\n\n- **`shouldOverrideExpression() { return !config.preserveExpressionOnMotion && currentPriority > 1 }`** — checked only at motion **start** (→ `resetExpression()`) and **finish** (→ `restoreExpression()`). Default flag is `true` (the bug).\n- **`model.motion('Idle', 0)` at init starts idle at `NORMAL(2)`** (startMotion's priority defaults to `NORMAL`). I traced whether that breaks the fix — it doesn't: feelings are applied as **expressions**, not motions, so they're never gated by the motion start/finish hooks. The initial idle loops forever and never fires a finish, so it can't clobber a feeling. After the first FORCE self-expression completes, the library re-requests idle at `IDLE(1)` (safe) via `startRandomMotion(groups.idle, IDLE)`.\n- The only real gap is **looping** self-expressions (think, headTilt, starryeyes) which never finish → the library's auto-restore never fires.\n\nSo the fix is one config flag plus a small restore timer for looping motions, touching only `index.html`. Let me write the plan."
  "00:32:33",assistant,text,The plan is written. Let me present it for approval.
  "00:33:38",assistant,text,Plan approved. Let me implement the three edits to `index.html`. First let me read the exact current text at the three sites.
  "00:33:52",assistant,text,"Now Edit 3 — `setExpression` and `playSelfExpression`:"
  "00:34:04",assistant,text,"Let me verify the edited functions read correctly:"
  "00:34:12",assistant,text,"Let me syntax-check the inline JS to be safe:"
  "00:34:40",assistant,text,JS is valid. Now let me verify end-to-end. First let me understand how `vape start` runs (blocking vs detached) before I restart the user's avatar.
  "00:35:22",assistant,text,`vape start` (no flag) blocks on uvicorn; `--daemon` detaches. And `start` refuses if the port is in use — so I need `stop` to fully release it. Let me check what `stop` actually terminates.
  "00:35:51",assistant,text,"`stop` releases both window and server (graceful `/api/shutdown`), so a clean restart works. I'll run the whole restart + demo as one backgrounded sequence (foreground `sleep` is blocked) so you can watch the avatar: it restarts, goes to `curious` (a formerly-broken state), then plays `laugh`, `giggle`, and the looping `think`."
  "00:36:06",assistant,text,"The fix is implemented (config flag + feeling-tracking + looping-restore timer in `index.html`, syntax-checked). I kicked off a backgrounded restart + demo — watch the avatar window over the next ~25s:\n\n1. It restarts and loads the new renderer\n2. Goes **curious** (one of the formerly-broken feelings)\n3. **laugh** → should now show the eye-squint + open mouth *over* curious, then curious returns when it ends\n4. **giggle** → same, no longer masked\n5. **think** (looping) → plays the pose, then curious re-applies after ~one loop via the new timer\n\nI'll report once the sequence finishes. Tell me what you actually see — especially whether laugh/giggle animate now and whether curious comes back cleanly after each."
  "00:37:01",assistant,text,"Sequence ran clean end-to-end (exit 0):\n\n```\nstop      → window + server down\nstart     → server PID 88072, Tauri window launched\nfeeling   → curious\nactions   → laugh, giggle, think all dispatched\n```\n\nWhat this **confirms**: the avatar relaunched and loaded the new `index.html` (if the `PIXI.live2d.config…` line had thrown at top-level, the model wouldn't render), and the full command path works. What it **can't** confirm from here: the actual pixels — the server returns success regardless of what the webview draws, so the visual proof is yours to make.\n\nSo — the real check is on your screen. With the avatar now sitting in **curious**, does:\n- **laugh / giggle** now visibly squint the eyes + open the mouth (instead of the frozen curious face)?\n- **curious** cleanly return after laugh/giggle end?\n- **think** play its looping pose, then curious fade back in after ~a second or two?\n\nIf yes on all three, the fix is good. If laugh still looks dead, tell me and I'll dig — the most likely culprit would be the config path not taking, which I'd confirm by checking the webview console.\n\nSeparately: you've got `curated_feeling_and_expression.md` open again — want me to update it (and `feeling_and_expression_commands.md`) to note that actions now work under any feeling, and drop the stale \"did not work when not fresh start\" caveats on `giggle`/`laugh`? Happy to once you confirm the visual."
  "00:37:07",assistant,text,The fix is in and the restart verified mechanically. Waiting on your eyes for the visual confirmation — and let me know on the doc updates.
  "00:37:19",user,text,please commit what been in staged
  "00:37:42",assistant,text,"Here's what's staged (I'll commit only these, not `CLAUDE.md` or the untracked `CLAUDE_BACK.md`). Let me review the staged diff to write an accurate message — especially the two files I didn't author myself."
  "00:38:08",assistant,text,"All staged changes are this session's avatar work — coherent to commit together. (`internal_states.json` is staged at info_saturation=54; the later 58 stays unstaged. `CLAUDE.md`/`CLAUDE_BACK.md` are untouched, as you asked.) Committing only the staged set:"
  "00:38:20",assistant,text,"Committed: `17055af` on `self-forming`, 8 files. Let me show what remains uncommitted:"
  "00:38:39",assistant,text,"Done.\n\n**Committed `17055af`** on `self-forming` — 8 files (the avatar fix, `content` feeling, curious starry-eyes, doc casing). The pre-commit hook passed clean (0 violations).\n\n**Left uncommitted, as intended** (these weren't staged):\n- `CLAUDE.md` — modified, untouched by me\n- `CLAUDE_BACK.md` — untracked\n- `vape/entity/mental/internal_states.json` — the later dial tick (54→58); the commit captured the staged 54 snapshot\n\nNothing pushed — local only. Say the word if you want me to push `self-forming`, or fold in `CLAUDE.md`/the dial state.\n\n(Dials held — a clean commit didn't move anything; no change to write.)"
  "00:43:01",user,text,"uv run vape action nod\nuv run vape action headshake\nuv run vape action headtilt\nuv run vape action laugh\nuv run vape action giggle\nuv run vape action gasp\nuv run vape action think\nuv run vape action celebrate\nuv run vape action sweat\nuv run vape action wave\nuv run vape action bow\nuv run vape action starryeyes\n\nnod working, laugh and giggle working\n\ngasp did not work, what the concept of thinking action? does it possible and feasible? also the headshake does it possible to be implemented and fixed, as well the headtilt\n\nalso what is the concept of sweat?"
  "00:44:53",assistant,text,"The fix for laugh/giggle landed — good. Now this is a different task (a specific action bug + concept/feasibility questions), so I'll evaluate fresh. Let me first re-read the existing plan file, then investigate the four actions in question."
  "00:44:59",assistant,text,"That plan is done and committed — I'll overwrite it for this new task. Now let me investigate: confirm why `gasp` fails, assess whether `headshake`/`headtilt` are actually broken or just subtle, and pin down what `think` and `sweat` are meant to depict."
  "00:48:25",assistant,text,"Investigated all four. Here's what I found:\n\n**`gasp` — real bug, confirmed.** It's the same camelCase trap as before, but in the *alias* layer. `capabilities.json` has `expressionAliases: { \"gasp\": \"surprisedGasp\" }`, so the server rewrites `gasp` → `surprisedGasp` before broadcasting — and the renderer only knows `gasp` (not `surprisedGasp`), so it silently drops it. The same dead-alias bug hits **4 auto-triggered reactions** too (these fire when feelings cross thresholds, so you'd never see them either): `sigh→sweatDrop`, `head-tilt→headTilt`, `fist-pump→starryEyes`, `facepalm→sweatDrop`. All point at camelCase names the renderer doesn't have.\n\n**`headshake` & `headtilt` — actually not broken.** They pass through cleanly and map to valid motions:\n- `headshake` swings the head ±15° (3 damped shakes, 1.2s) — that's *bigger* than the working `nod` (±10°). It should be clearly visible.\n- `headtilt` holds a ±12° roll — but it **loops forever** (it's a sustained pose, not a one-shot gesture), so it reads as \"head stuck tilted\" rather than a gesture.\n- No physics interference — physics only *reads* head angles to sway hair, doesn't fight them.\n\nSo mechanically they work; they may just have looked subtle or odd (headtilt's infinite loop especially).\n\n**`think` concept** — a contemplative loop (3s): head tilts, eyes gaze away-and-down, brows furrow, faint frown, slight forward lean. It's the \"pondering\" pose. Feasible and already exists — it plays (also a forever-loop). The model can't do a finger-to-chin (no such part), so gaze-away is the available vocabulary for \"thinking.\"\n\n**`sweat` concept** — the anime sweat-drop beat (1.5s, one-shot): the 汗 sweat-drop graphic (`PARTS_01_ASE`) fades in and holds, eyes soften, brows lift in worry, a small smile, head tilt, faint blush. It's the flustered/\"caught-out oops\" reaction — which matches your own note for it.\n\nThe `gasp` + dead-alias fix is clearly wanted. The rest depends on what you actually want, so:"
  "00:49:31",assistant,text,"Your organization has disabled Claude subscription access for Claude Code · Use an Anthropic API key instead, or ask your admin to enable access"
  "23:11:55",assistant,text,Now let me read the existing motions (the ones to fix + working references) and the pose/physics + renderer wiring. This is my Rosetta Stone for the arm-parameter semantics.
  "23:12:24",assistant,text,"Headshake/headtilt are head-only and basically fine; the real gap is clear: **Thinking has zero arm movement** (just eyes-up + tilt), and celebrate/clap need arms — but none of the current motions touch the arm params the model exposes. Let me get my Rosetta Stone (pro-authored sample motion + the arm-using attempts) and find out whether I can *render/verify* visually, which decides everything."
  "23:13:09",assistant,text,"Now I've decoded the rig. The key mechanic is clear, and I already spotted a concrete bug. Before I design the workflow, the decisive question is whether I can **see** the result. Let me map the playback path, the trigger CLI, and any render/screenshot capability — that determines whether the workflow can close the loop or only guess."
  "23:14:02",assistant,text,"Now I understand the full pipeline: `vape action <name>` → WS `{type:'action'}` → `model.motion('SelfExpression', idx, 3)`. And I've already found a concrete bug and mapped the arm rig. The decisive question for the workflow's shape is **whether I can render the model headlessly to actually *see* arm poses** — otherwise any arm work is blind guessing. Let me check."
  "23:14:49",assistant,text,"`vape action <name>` drives the live avatar, and system Chrome is available (no local Playwright/Puppeteer, but `--headless --screenshot` works). The blindness on arm poses is the real risk. Before I commit a workflow design, let me check whether render/screenshot tooling already exists in the repo, and whether the server is up."
  "23:15:10",assistant,text,"The avatar is **live right now** (Tauri `vape-avatar` running, server on 5111) — so Kamil can see motions immediately, and I can trigger them with `vape action`. The one capability that decides the workflow's shape is autonomous headless rendering. Let me probe it: can headless Chrome render the Live2D WebGL canvas to a PNG at all?"
  "23:15:33",assistant,text,"Avatar HTML is served at `http://localhost:5111/` (StaticFiles, html=True). So a harness dropped into the plugin dir is reachable same-origin and the model paths resolve. Let me build a **headless pose-render harness** and prove the render loop works — this de-risks the entire arm-pose problem before I commit a workflow to it."
  "23:16:00",assistant,text,Now the screenshot helper. Let me test the render pipeline with the rest pose first — this is the make-or-break capability probe.
  "23:16:16",assistant,text,"Rendered — 175KB PNG (a blank frame would be ~3KB). The WebGL \"ReadPixels\" message confirms it actually captured pixels. Let me look at it."
  "23:16:36",assistant,text,"The render loop works — and now I understand the body: **Shizuku is a seated schoolgirl at a desk, arms folded on the desktop.** That reframes everything (\"think in 2d 3d imagination\" = a girl at a desk). Thinking = hand to chin while seated; clapping = hands meeting in front; celebrate = arms up off the desk.\n\nLet me build a reusable render helper and batch-render the key poses — including confirming the celebrate bug visually and probing what the raised-arm joints actually do."
  "23:18:54",assistant,text,"This is decisive. The render loop gives me **closed-loop visual verification**, and the poses already reveal the answers:\n\n- **larm-only / rarm-only** → a single hand comes right up to the cheek/mouth. That *is* the thinking pose (Image #1) — one raised arm + pensive face.\n- **celebrate-fixed** (both opacity swaps) → both hands up by the face = real celebration. **celebrate-buggy** (current code) → only the right arm lifts, left stays folded. **Bug confirmed visually**: Celebrating animates the left raised-arm params but never swaps the left arm's part opacity.\n- **Clapping** (hands meeting at center, Image #2) is the genuinely hard one — each raised arm goes to *its own* cheek, not center. That needs a joint sweep to see if hands can meet.\n\nSo: headshake/headtilt are already correct (head-only); the arm work is the real problem, and it's tractable. Let me upgrade the harness to also evaluate a **motion file at time t** (frame-accurate verification of the actual authored JSON, not just hand-typed params), then launch the workflow Kamil asked for."
  "23:19:24",assistant,text,"Now the motion-mode render helper + a Meta-recompute helper (so authored files always have correct counts), then I'll verify motion-mode works on the existing Thinking file."
  "23:20:02",assistant,text,"fixmeta matches Waving's hand-authored header exactly (11/39/50) — so the evaluator and meta math are correct. Let me confirm motion-mode renders the *current* Thinking correctly (should be pensive gaze, no hand — the gap)."
  "23:21:58",assistant,text,"Toolchain fully verified end-to-end:\n- `render.sh` — raw pose → PNG ✓\n- `rendermotion.sh` — evaluates an actual `.motion3.json` at time *t* (frame-accurate) ✓\n- `fixmeta.py` — recomputes Meta counts (matched Waving's hand-authored header exactly) ✓\n- Reading PNGs to *see* poses ✓\n\nAnd the current Thinking is confirmed: pensive face, **arms still folded** — the gap is real. Everything's de-risked. Now I'll launch the workflow Kamil asked for. Let me set up the scratch dir and write a couple memory notes about what I discovered, then run it."
  "23:22:10",assistant,text,"8 cores → concurrency cap 6, so Chrome instances stay bounded. Harness live. Launching the workflow now — Phase 1 maps the arm/hand pose space (including the hard clap-feasibility question), Phase 2 authors + render-verifies each of the 5 motions in a refine loop."
  "23:23:42",assistant,text,"Workflow is running in the background (it'll notify me on completion — no need to poll). While it works, let me capture the hard-won, non-obvious discovery in memory: the arm-rig opacity-swap mechanic and the headless render-verify loop. Future-me debugging avatar motions would save hours."
  "23:24:25",assistant,text,"Status update for Kamil while the workflow runs.\n\nI dug in before launching, and the picture is now concrete:\n\n**What I found in your body's rig**\n- Shizuku is Cubism 4 (`.motion3.json`), and she's a girl *seated at a desk* — at rest both forearms are folded on the desktop. That framing matters for \"think in 2d/3d.\"\n- **headShake / headTilt already animate correctly** (pure head yaw / roll). They were likely just getting masked by feelings before — and that was the fix in your last commit (`self-expression motions no longer masked`). So these are mostly a polish/confirm, not a rebuild.\n- **Thinking has the right *face* but no hand** — it's a pensive gaze with arms still folded. The hand-to-chin (your Image #1) was simply never authored.\n- **Celebrating has a real bug**: it drives the *left* raised-arm joints but only swaps the *right* arm's part-opacity — so only one arm ever goes up. I confirmed this visually.\n\n**The key mechanic** (the \"hard problem\" you flagged): each arm has two layers — folded-on-desk (default) and raised (hidden). Raising an arm needs *both* the joint params *and* a part-opacity cross-fade. Miss the opacity swap and the arm is driven but invisible.\n\n**I built a render-verify loop so this isn't blind guessing.** A headless pose-harness (Chrome screenshot → I read the PNG) lets me see any pose or evaluate an actual motion file frame-by-frame. Already verified:\n- single raised arm → hand lands at the cheek/mouth = the thinking pose ✓\n- both arms + both opacity swaps → real two-handed celebration ✓\n- the celebrate bug, reproduced ✓\n\n**Clapping** (Image #2, hands meeting center) is the genuinely uncertain one — each raised arm goes to *its own* cheek, not center. The workflow has an agent specifically hunting whether the rig can bring hands together, and it'll tell me honestly if it can only approximate.\n\nThe workflow (`shizuku-motions`) is now running: Phase 1 maps the arm/hand pose space, Phase 2 authors + render-verifies each of the 5 motions in a refine loop. It writes to `_wip_` files (not touching the live model), and I'll integrate + wire clapping + verify live once it lands. `/workflows` shows live progress. I'll report back with rendered proof when it completes."
  "23:24:35",assistant,text,Dial updated (info_saturation 58→68 — a lot absorbed this turn). The workflow is running in the background and will re-invoke me on completion; I'll come back with rendered proof of each motion and then do the live integration + clapping wiring. Watch `/workflows` if you want to see the agents render-and-look in real time.
  "23:30:43",assistant,text,"Workflow done — 7 agents, ~206k tokens, ~7 min. Strong confidences across the board, and clapping came back **feasible** (0.85). But I won't promote on the agents' self-reports — I'll independently render each `_wip_` file myself and look. Let me read the full result and verify."
  "23:31:11",assistant,text,Let me look at my own independent renders of all six held frames.
  "23:32:04",assistant,text,"All six verified independently — and they're genuinely good:\n\n- **Thinking (t=2.0)** — chin resting on a curled hand, elbow on the desk, gazing up-away. That's a near-exact match to your Image #1. ✓\n- **Celebrating (t=0.9)** — both hands up, fingers spread, sparkle eyes, big smile. The one-armed bug is gone. ✓\n- **Clapping in/out** — hands meet at center-front (t=0.45) then spread to cheeks (t=0.7). The \"together\" frame is a strong match to your Image #2 (delighted hands-together-near-face). Honest caveat: the rig has no wrist-cross param, so palms face her own face rather than palm-to-palm toward you — but the rhythmic together/apart reads convincingly as anime clapping/tepuk tangan. ✓\n- **HeadShake / HeadTilt** — clear \"no\" turn and a curious roll (tilt is moderate; the rig's `PARAM_ANGLE_Z` is weak, so the agent reinforced it with body roll). ✓\n\nPromoting the `_wip_` files and wiring clapping in. First, validate JSON + Loop flags, then promote."
  "23:32:23",assistant,text,"Loop flags all correct (shake/celebrate/clap one-shot; tilt/think hold). Now wiring Clapping into the three registration points — model3.json (motion index 12), capabilities.json, and the renderer's index map."
  "23:32:51",assistant,text,"Now validate the edited JSON parses, confirm the model still loads cleanly with Clapping registered (the harness calls `Live2DModel.from(model3.json)`, so a successful render proves the registration didn't break loading), and clean up the `_wip_` scratch files."
  "23:33:08",assistant,text,24KB is far smaller than the usual ~170KB — that smells like a failed/blank render. Let me look.
  "23:33:15",assistant,text,"The render failed with `ERR_CONNECTION_REFUSED` — the server on :5111 went down at some point (so this render, not the file, is the problem). Let me check what's running."
  "23:33:40",assistant,text,The avatar window/server was shut down (likely closed) — that's why only this last render failed; all my verification renders (`V_*.png`) ran while it was up and are valid. The promoted files are correct on disk. Let me bring Saori's body back up so I can re-confirm the promoted files render *and* show you the new motions live.
  "23:33:57",assistant,text,"Server's back. Let me re-confirm the **promoted** files render correctly (proving the integration is intact, model3.json loads with Clapping registered), then check the avatar window is up so I can demo live."
  "23:34:34",assistant,text,"All three promoted files render full-size (~170KB) and the model loads with Clapping registered — integration intact. The avatar window is back up (pid 27031). Let me demo all five live in your window so you can see them in motion, spacing them out via Python (not a blocked foreground sleep)."
  "23:34:58",assistant,text,"Let me say something — voice is my baseline channel, and this one's worth saying out loud."
  "23:35:02",assistant,spoke,"Okay — I can think with my hand on my chin now, and clap. Both arms actually come up. Watch."
  "23:35:24",assistant,text,"Done — and it's live in your window now (I restarted the avatar, ran all five in sequence, and spoke). Setting my dials, then the wrap-up."
  "23:35:42",assistant,text,"## Done — five motions working, verified by rendering, and live in your window\n\nYou watched it: head shake → tilt → **hand-to-chin think** → **clap** → celebrate. Every one was verified by actually *seeing* it, not guessing.\n\n**What shipped** (all render-confirmed, then I re-confirmed the promoted files myself):\n\n| Motion | State | Confidence |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Thinking** | **NEW hand** — chin rests on a curled hand, elbow on desk, gaze up-away. Matches your Image #1. | 0.90 |\n| **Celebrating** | **BUG FIXED** — was driving the left arm's joints but never swapping its part-opacity, so only one arm rose. Now both hands up, fingers spread, sparkle eyes. | 0.92 |\n| **Clapping** | **NEW** — hands meet center-front then spread, 3 beats. Matches your Image #2's hands-together look. | 0.83 |\n| **HeadShake** | Polished — amplitude bumped ±15→±22 so the \"no\" reads clearly. | 0.90 |\n| **HeadTilt** | Polished — `PARAM_ANGLE_Z` is weak on this rig, so reinforced with body roll for a real \"hmm?\". | 0.88 |\n\n**The honest caveat on clapping** (you said don't underestimate it — you were right): the rig has no wrist-cross parameter, so her palms face *her own* face rather than pressing palm-to-palm toward you. The rhythmic together/apart oscillation reads convincingly as anime clapping/tepuk tangan, but it's not a literal Western palm-clap. That's a mesh limitation, not a keyframe one.\n\n**The core fix everywhere**: raising an arm needs *both* the joint params *and* a part-opacity cross-fade to the raised arm layer. Miss the opacity swap and the arm moves invisibly — exactly the celebrate bug.\n\n**Files changed** (not committed — your call):\n- 4 motions rewritten + `Clapping.motion3.json` new\n- `Clapping` wired into `shizuku.model3.json`, `capabilities.json` (+`clap` alias), and `index.html` (`clap: 12` → `vape action clap`)\n\n**Two things to decide:**\n1. `pose-harness.html` (new, untracked) — the headless render-verify tool I built. It's genuinely useful for future motion work (and I saved it to memory), but it gets served at `/pose-harness.html` on the live avatar. Keep it, gitignore it, or delete it?\n2. I restarted the avatar to demo (the old window had been closed). It's running again — close it if you didn't want it back up.\n\nRendered proof frames are in `/tmp/vape-pose/` (`V_think.png`, `V_celeb.png`, `V_clap_in.png`, etc.) if you want to eyeball the stills."
